@Andrzej 
Honest question:
Is the word "entree" ever used (unaltered) in Polish? If so, does it have the original French meaning of "appetizer" or "first course," or the modern American one of "main course"?

@Bill 

We only use Polish words in menus, so no entree conundrum for us. An appetizer is przystawka, then we would have the first course, pierwsze danie, traditionally a soup, then the second course, drugie danie, traditionally meat with potatoes and a salad, then dessert, deser.

French was commonly used in fancy Warsaw restaurants before 1939, so I bet all the words then had their original French meanings.

@Barry Ancona 

It must have been a bot that intervened (moderately?) because the post just did not appear. It may have been because I used the word for the political system in Poland after 1944, beginning with c - perhaps in American election season that's a no-no? I find all this very strange - a normal word used to describe the world suddenly becomes taboo because some people use it too eagerly and inaccurately?

Anyway, Wajda's films are quintessentially Polish, and as such they must be very hard to fully understand by foreigners: that's the gist of my longer, quashed post.

